---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import SectionDivider from '../components/SectionDivider.astro';
import SourceLink from '../components/SourceLink.astro';
import SourceList from '../components/SourceList.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    title: 'Nammoona Landfill — Cell 6A completion',
    publisher: 'Richmond Valley Council',
    url: 'https://www.richmondvalley.nsw.gov.au/',
    note: 'Managing-waste page. URL to confirm specific cell reference.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Stotts Creek Resource Recovery Centre — Cell C and organics facility',
    publisher: 'Tweed Shire Council',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'North East Waste — regional waste data and member councils',
    publisher: 'North East Waste (NE Waste)',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'North Coast Region Waste Investment Report',
    publisher: 'NSW Government',
    date: '2020',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Three alternative approaches"
  description="The real alternatives to a new Blakebrook landfill are not other holes to dig. They are which existing licensed facilities to invest in — Nammoona, Stotts Creek, Grafton — and how to shrink the residual waste stream first."
  progress
  article
>
  <PageHeader eyebrow="Alternatives" title="Three alternative approaches">
    The question isn&rsquo;t really &ldquo;where else could we dig a new
    hole.&rdquo; Three operating regional landfills already exist within
    trucking distance, and Lismore has been shipping to Ipswich since 2022. The
    real choice is which existing infrastructure to invest in — and how to
    reduce the residual stream in the first place.
  </PageHeader>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-prose px-5 pb-8">
    <div class="prose-body mt-10">
      <SectionDivider>Alternative 1</SectionDivider>
      <h2>Expand Nammoona (Casino, Richmond Valley)</h2>
      <p>
        Nammoona is an existing licensed regional landfill; its Cell 6A was
        completed in 2024.<SourceLink n={1} /> It sits in the drier inland zone
        with rail and highway access, co-located with an industrial corridor,
        and is hydrogeologically less sensitive than the Wilsons River
        headwaters. A funded regional partnership at Nammoona avoids building a
        new greenfield site in a rainforest-fringe catchment.
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>Alternative 2</SectionDivider>
      <h2>Networked expansion across existing facilities</h2>
      <p>
        Tweed has recently invested in Cell C and a major organics processing
        facility at Stotts Creek.<SourceLink n={2} /> Grafton operates the
        Clarence Valley regional landfill. Rather than concentrating a
        seven-council waste stream in one new site, the region could fund staged
        cell expansions across the <strong>three existing licensed
        facilities</strong> under a North East Waste regional agreement.<SourceLink
          n={3}
        /> Each already has monitoring infrastructure, community familiarity and
        operating staff. The result: lower capital cost, distributed risk, and
        no new sacrifice zone.
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>Alternative 3</SectionDivider>
      <h2>Properly-sited brownfield co-location</h2>
      <p>
        If a genuinely new site is required, the right siting criteria are clear:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>above the 1% AEP flood plain;</li>
        <li>
          away from sensitive surface waters (100 m minimum, per the Queensland
          guideline);
        </li>
        <li>more than 500 m from sensitive receptors;</li>
        <li>low-permeability geology with deep groundwater;</li>
        <li>
          already-degraded land — closed quarries, cleared agricultural land on
          stable plateaus;
        </li>
        <li>
          road or rail access that does not route trucks through residential
          villages.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The Casino&ndash;Lismore industrial corridor contains pockets that meet
        these criteria. A site-selection process weighted on <strong
          >environmental risk</strong
        > — rather than on council land ownership and existing quarry voids —
        would have started there.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div
      class="mt-12 rounded-lg border-l-2 border-ochre bg-white/40 px-5 py-5 font-body text-[0.95rem] italic leading-relaxed text-ink/85"
    >
      <p>
        We are not nominating private parcels. That is irresponsible advocacy
        and the council&rsquo;s job, not ours. We are saying that the published
        site-selection process appears to have weighted land availability over
        siting criteria, and that several legitimate alternative approaches were
        not seriously canvassed in public.
      </p>
    </div>

    <SourceList sources={sources} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
